{
  "In the exponential growth model, the equation dN/dt = rN assumes that:": "",
  "The population is at carrying capacity": "",
  "The death rate exceeds the birth rate": "",
  "Resources are limited and competition occurs": "",
  "The population has unlimited resources and no environmental resistance": "",
  "The exponential growth model assumes ideal conditions with unlimited resources, no predation, no disease, and no competition. Under these assumptions, the population grows at a constant per capita rate (r), producing a J-shaped growth curve.": "",
  "In the logistic growth model, what happens to population growth rate as N approaches K?": "",
  "Growth rate increases exponentially": "",
  "Growth rate becomes negative permanently": "",
  "Growth rate approaches zero": "",
  "Growth rate remains constant": "",
  "In the logistic growth model (dN/dt = rN(K-N)/K), as the population size N approaches the carrying capacity K, the term (K-N)/K approaches zero, which reduces the growth rate to near zero. This creates the characteristic S-shaped sigmoid curve.": "",
  "The intrinsic rate of natural increase (r) in a population is calculated as:": "",
  "Death rate minus birth rate": "",
  "Birth rate minus death rate": "",
  "Birth rate divided by death rate": "",
  "Birth rate multiplied by death rate": "",
  "The intrinsic rate of natural increase (r) equals the per capita birth rate (b) minus the per capita death rate (d). When r is positive, the population grows; when r is negative, the population declines; and when r equals zero, the population is stable.": "",
  "A population growing exponentially will produce which type of growth curve?": "",
  "J-shaped curve": "",
  "Bell-shaped curve": "",
  "Linear straight line": "",
  "S-shaped (sigmoid) curve": "",
  "Exponential growth produces a J-shaped curve because the population grows by an increasingly large amount in each time period. The steepness of the curve increases over time as the larger population produces more offspring, accelerating growth.": "",
  "Which of the following is a density-dependent factor that limits population growth?": "",
  "Competition for limited food resources": "",
  "A volcanic eruption": "",
  "A severe drought": "",
  "A hurricane destroying habitat": "",
  "Competition for food is density-dependent because its intensity increases as population density rises. At higher densities, more individuals compete for the same resources, leading to reduced per capita food availability, lower reproduction, and higher mortality.": "",
  "The logistic growth equation dN/dt = rN(K-N)/K includes the term (K-N)/K, which represents:": "",
  "The birth rate of the population": "",
  "The fraction of carrying capacity still available for population growth": "",
  "The maximum population size": "",
  "The death rate of the population": "",
  "The term (K-N)/K represents the proportion of the carrying capacity that remains unused. When N is small relative to K, this fraction is close to 1 and growth is nearly exponential. As N approaches K, this fraction approaches zero, slowing growth.": "",
  "At what population size does a logistically growing population achieve its maximum growth rate?": "",
  "When N equals K": "",
  "When N is at its lowest point": "",
  "When N equals K/2": "",
  "When N exceeds K": "",
  "In the logistic model, the maximum growth rate (dN/dt) occurs when the population is at half the carrying capacity (N = K/2). At this point, the combination of population size and remaining resources produces the greatest absolute increase in population per unit time.": "",
  "Which statement best describes r-selected species?": "",
  "They produce many offspring quickly with little parental investment": "",
  "They have long lifespans and late maturity": "",
  "They produce few offspring with extensive parental care": "",
  "Their populations are typically near carrying capacity": "",
  "R-selected species are characterized by high reproductive rates, early maturity, small body size, and minimal parental care. They thrive in unpredictable or disturbed environments where the ability to reproduce quickly and colonize new areas provides a survival advantage.": "",
  "If a population has a growth rate (r) of 0.02 per year, approximately how many years will it take for the population to double?": "",
  "50 years": "",
  "20 years": "",
  "35 years": "",
  "70 years": "",
  "The doubling time can be approximated using the Rule of 70: doubling time = 70 / (growth rate as a percentage). With r = 0.02 (2%), the doubling time is 70/2 = 35 years. This rule provides a quick estimate for exponentially growing populations.": "",
  "A survivorship curve that shows high mortality early in life followed by high survival for those that reach adulthood is classified as:": "",
  "Type IV": "",
  "Type II": "",
  "Type I": "",
  "Type III": "",
  "Type III survivorship curves show very high mortality rates among juveniles but high survival rates for individuals that survive to adulthood. Species like sea turtles, fish, and insects that produce many offspring with little parental care typically exhibit this pattern.": "",
  "What is carrying capacity (K)?": "",
  "The maximum growth rate a population can achieve": "",
  "The rate at which a population consumes resources": "",
  "The minimum population size needed to avoid extinction": "",
  "The maximum number of individuals of a species that an environment can sustainably support over time": "",
  "Carrying capacity (K) is the maximum population size that an environment can sustain indefinitely given available resources such as food, water, shelter, and space. It is a dynamic value that can change as environmental conditions change.": "",
  "What is the Rule of 70 used to calculate?": "",
  "The approximate doubling time of an exponentially growing population": "",
  "The carrying capacity of an ecosystem": "",
  "The extinction probability of a small population": "",
  "The maximum sustainable yield of a fishery": "",
  "The Rule of 70 states that the doubling time of an exponentially growing population equals 70 divided by the growth rate expressed as a percentage. For example, a population growing at 2% per year will double in approximately 70/2 = 35 years.": "",
  "What is a density-independent factor?": "",
  "A factor that affects population size regardless of the population's density": "",
  "A factor that only affects populations at high densities": "",
  "A factor that increases population growth rate as density rises": "",
  "A factor whose impact depends on how crowded the population is": "",
  "Density-independent factors affect populations regardless of their size or density. Natural disasters, extreme weather events, and seasonal changes are examples that kill or displace a proportion of the population without regard to how many individuals are present.": "",
  "What is a survivorship curve?": "",
  "A graph showing the proportion of individuals surviving to each age in a population": "",
  "A diagram showing the age structure of a population": "",
  "A graph showing the growth rate of a population over time": "",
  "A chart comparing birth rates across different species": "",
  "A survivorship curve plots the proportion of a cohort still alive at each successive age. The three standard types (I, II, III) describe different patterns of mortality across a lifespan and reflect different life history strategies among species.": "",
  "What is environmental resistance?": "",
  "The physical barriers that prevent species migration": "",
  "An ecosystem's ability to withstand pollution": "",
  "The genetic ability of a population to resist disease": "",
  "The combined effect of all environmental factors that limit population growth": "",
  "Environmental resistance is the sum of all biotic and abiotic factors that prevent a population from growing exponentially. These include predation, disease, competition, limited resources, and adverse weather, which collectively determine the carrying capacity.": "",
  "What does the term 'biotic potential' mean?": "",
  "The actual growth rate observed in a natural population": "",
  "The minimum number of offspring needed for population replacement": "",
  "The maximum reproductive rate of a population under ideal conditions with unlimited resources": "",
  "The carrying capacity of a given environment": "",
  "Biotic potential is the maximum rate of reproduction and population growth that a species can achieve under ideal environmental conditions. It represents the upper limit of population growth when there are no limiting factors such as disease, predation, or resource scarcity.": "",
  "What is a K-selected species?": "",
  "A species characterized by slower growth, longer lifespan, fewer offspring, and greater parental investment": "",
  "A species that reproduces rapidly with many small offspring": "",
  "A species that only lives near the equator": "",
  "A species that goes extinct quickly in disturbed environments": "",
  "K-selected species are adapted to stable environments and tend to have populations near carrying capacity. They invest heavily in fewer offspring through long gestation periods, extensive parental care, and late maturity. Examples include elephants, whales, and humans.": "",
  "What is a population bottleneck?": "",
  "The maximum size a population can reach in a given habitat": "",
  "A period when a population grows exponentially without limits": "",
  "A drastic reduction in population size that reduces genetic diversity": "",
  "The migration of individuals into a new geographic area": "",
  "A population bottleneck occurs when a population undergoes a dramatic size reduction due to a catastrophic event, reducing its genetic diversity. Even if the population recovers in numbers, the lost genetic variation can reduce the population's ability to adapt to future environmental changes.": "",
  "What is the difference between immigration and emigration in population ecology?": "",
  "Immigration is birth and emigration is death": "",
  "Immigration applies only to humans while emigration applies to animals": "",
  "Both terms describe the same process of population movement": "",
  "Immigration is the movement of individuals into a population, while emigration is the movement out": "",
  "Immigration adds individuals to a population when they move in from elsewhere, while emigration removes individuals when they move out. Together with births and deaths, immigration and emigration determine the overall change in population size over time.": "",
  "What is the minimum viable population (MVP)?": "",
  "The optimal population size for maximum growth rate": "",
  "The number of species needed for a stable ecosystem": "",
  "The maximum number of individuals a habitat can support": "",
  "The smallest population size that can sustain itself and avoid extinction over a specified time period": "",
  "The minimum viable population is the smallest number of individuals needed for a population to have a high probability of surviving over a specified time period, typically 100 or 1,000 years. Below this threshold, populations face increased risks from genetic drift, inbreeding, and random events.": "",
  "A population of rabbits on an island starts at 50 individuals with r = 0.1 per month and K = 500. Using the logistic growth model, which prediction is most accurate for the first few months?": "",
  "Growth rate will be at its maximum because N = K/2": "",
  "Growth will be slow because the population is near carrying capacity": "",
  "The population will immediately decline due to predation": "",
  "Growth will be nearly exponential because N is much less than K, so (K-N)/K is close to 1": "",
  "When N (50) is much smaller than K (500), the logistic correction factor (K-N)/K equals 450/500 = 0.9, which is close to 1. This means the population grows nearly exponentially during the early phase when resources are abundant relative to population size.": "",
  "An ecologist studying a deer population calculates that K = 1,000 and the current population is 600. The population's growth rate (r) is 0.3 per year. Using the logistic growth equation, approximately how many deer will be added to the population in one year?": "",
  "180 deer": "",
  "600 deer": "",
  "300 deer": "",
  "72 deer": "",
  "Using the logistic equation: dN/dt = rN(K-N)/K = 0.3 x 600 x (1000-600)/1000 = 0.3 x 600 x 0.4 = 72 deer per year. The growth is significantly slowed compared to exponential growth (which would add 180) because the population has already used 60% of the carrying capacity.": "",
  "A wildlife manager wants to maximize the sustainable harvest from a deer population with K = 2,000. According to the logistic growth model, at what population size should the herd be maintained to maximize annual harvest?": "",
  "1,500 deer": "",
  "1,000 deer": "",
  "2,000 deer": "",
  "500 deer": "",
  "Maximum sustainable yield occurs at N = K/2. With K = 2,000, the population should be maintained at 1,000 deer. At this size, the population produces the greatest surplus of individuals per year that can be harvested without reducing the population below this optimal level.": "",
  "A country's population is 10 million, with a birth rate of 30 per 1,000 and a death rate of 10 per 1,000 per year. Ignoring migration, what is the population growth rate and approximate doubling time?": "",
  "r = 1%, doubling time approximately 70 years": "",
  "r = 2%, doubling time approximately 35 years": "",
  "r = 3%, doubling time approximately 23 years": "",
  "r = 4%, doubling time approximately 18 years": "",
  "The growth rate r = (birth rate - death rate)/1000 = (30-10)/1000 = 0.02 or 2%. Using the Rule of 70: doubling time = 70/2 = 35 years. This means the population would grow from 10 million to 20 million in approximately 35 years without changes in birth or death rates.": "",
  "Two species of Paramecium are grown separately and each thrives in the lab. When placed together in the same culture with limited resources, one species declines to extinction while the other persists. This experiment demonstrates:": "",
  "Predator-prey dynamics, particularly regarding will based on the prevailing evidence": "",
  "Mutualism between closely related species in most standard conditions": "",
  "Density-independent mortality, particularly regarding typically as determined by": "",
  "The competitive exclusion principle, where two species cannot coexist on the same limiting resource": "",
  "This is Gause's classic competitive exclusion experiment. When two species compete for identical resources in a uniform environment, the species with even a slight competitive advantage will eventually exclude the other. This principle explains why coexisting species typically partition resources.": "",
  "A population of bacteria in a lab culture shows the following pattern: slow initial growth, rapid exponential increase, then leveling off. When graphed, this produces an S-shaped curve. A student asks why the growth slowed. What is the best explanation?": "",
  "The temperature in the lab decreased over time": "",
  "The bacteria reached their maximum possible lifespan": "",
  "The bacteria mutated to reproduce more slowly": "",
  "As the population grew, resources became scarce and waste products accumulated, increasing environmental resistance": "",
  "The S-shaped logistic growth curve results from density-dependent factors. As bacteria multiplied, nutrients became depleted and metabolic waste products accumulated, slowing reproduction and increasing death rates. This environmental resistance brought the population toward carrying capacity.": "",
  "A population of elk has K = 800 and currently has 800 individuals. A harsh winter kills 200 elk, reducing the population to 600. According to the logistic model, what will happen next?": "",
  "The population will remain stable at 600": "",
  "The carrying capacity will permanently drop to 600": "",
  "The population will continue to decline": "",
  "The population will grow back toward K = 800 because more resources are now available per individual": "",
  "When a population drops below carrying capacity, reduced competition for resources leads to increased survival and reproduction, driving population growth back toward K. At N = 600 with K = 800, the logistic term (K-N)/K = 0.25, allowing positive growth to occur.": "",
  "An ecologist compares two island bird populations of the same species. Island A has 50 birds and Island B has 500 birds. Both islands are hit by a severe storm that randomly kills 40% of birds on each island. Which population faces a greater risk of extinction and why?": "",
  "Island A, because the remaining 30 individuals may fall below the minimum viable population and are more vulnerable to random events": "",
  "Both face equal risk because the same percentage was killed": "",
  "Neither faces extinction risk from a single storm event": "",
  "Island B, because it loses more total individuals": "",
  "Small populations are more vulnerable to extinction from random events because they have fewer individuals to buffer losses. Island A's 30 survivors may fall below the minimum viable population, face genetic problems from inbreeding, and have a higher probability of extinction from subsequent random events.": "",
  "A fisheries biologist monitors a lake where bass have been overfished. She implements catch limits, and after five years the population has recovered to K/2. She recommends maintaining the population at this level. Why does K/2 represent the optimal management target?": "",
  "Because at K/2 there are no density-dependent effects": "",
  "Because K/2 is the smallest stable population size": "",
  "Because at K/2 the population produces its maximum surplus, allowing the greatest sustainable harvest": "",
  "Because at K/2 individual fish are largest and most valuable": "",
  "At N = K/2, the logistic growth model predicts maximum population growth rate (dN/dt). This means the population produces the largest surplus of individuals per year at this point. Harvesting this surplus allows the greatest sustained catch while keeping the population stable at K/2.": "",
  "A conservation biologist models two endangered species. Species A has r = 0.5 and K = 100. Species B has r = 0.05 and K = 10,000. Both populations are currently at 10% of their carrying capacity. If both face the same proportional habitat loss that reduces K by 50%, which species is likely more vulnerable to extinction?": "",
  "Species B, because it has a lower growth rate": "",
  "Both species are equally vulnerable because they lose the same proportion": "",
  "Species A, because it has a smaller carrying capacity and the 50% K reduction leaves fewer individuals to maintain genetic viability": "",
  "Neither species is at risk because they are both below their original K": "",
  "When K is reduced by 50%, Species A's new K becomes 50, leaving only about 10 individuals at 10% capacity. This is dangerously close to or below the minimum viable population, where genetic drift, inbreeding, and random events can drive extinction. Species B, with a new K of 5,000 and about 1,000 individuals, has a much larger buffer against extinction.": ""
}